{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"74a5f2a1-3a65-4dc1-9e0a-813fc02f2d6f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect the trace:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                        # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app/).\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want a browser-viewable file without Windows tools.\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead — it exposes trace collection via an HTTP API.\n- For very high CPU where managed sampling is unreliable, consider `perf record` + `dotnet-symbol` for native-level profiling, but `dotnet-trace` is the easiest starting point.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a07f2c08-24c8-4085-bade-95ffe4fd67d3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":395},"id":"6ef76020-111b-49d2-b753-cbc7a15bcd34","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:51:41.334Z","parentId":"c69311ea-d467-4096-8a4b-91403f9ca9d9"}
